  <mainDescription>&lt;h3>&#xD;
    Purpose&#xD;
&lt;/h3>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    This metric is used to identify the trend of work items that are blocking&amp;nbsp;the team&amp;nbsp;from making progress. It&#xD;
    can help you to identify&amp;nbsp;road blocks&amp;nbsp;and&amp;nbsp;focus on removing them so that&amp;nbsp;the team can move forward.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    This metric is useful when there are multiple teams working together. A high level of collaboration is needed due&#xD;
    to&amp;nbsp;interdependencies among the various tasks that teams are working on.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;h3>&#xD;
    Definition&#xD;
&lt;/h3>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Count: the total number of&amp;nbsp;open work items with a status of blocked in&amp;nbsp;the iteration.&amp;nbsp;&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;h3>&#xD;
    Analysis&#xD;
&lt;/h3>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    A good way to monitor Blocking Work Items is to use a line chart. Observe the growth of blocking work items over time.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Expected trend&lt;/strong> - The number of blocking work items should approach zero as the iteration nears its&#xD;
        end. This indicates the team is making progress and is positioned well to successfully complete the iteration.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Upward slope&lt;/strong> - When the number of blocking work items remains high, velocity is reduced and&#xD;
        can&amp;nbsp;impact the project schedule. This trend indicates that the team may not be working to identify potential&#xD;
        project risks. They may also be doing a poor job of managing issues to closure.&amp;nbsp;Watch for a &amp;nbsp;high or&#xD;
        increasing number of blocking work items close to the end of an iteration. This may indicate that the iteration end&#xD;
        date is in danger. The team should review each blocking work item on the report&amp;nbsp;to determine what is causing&#xD;
        the blockage. It is also important to&amp;nbsp;understand how long&amp;nbsp;each has been blocked. This information can&#xD;
        help you plan needed corrective action. When there are multiple teams working together collaboratively or on&#xD;
        high-dependency tasks, it is a good idea to create a dependency diagram to try to avoid the road blocking in the&#xD;
        critical path, or try to remove the blocking as soon as possible.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    In the&amp;nbsp;following example, which shows open blocking work items,&amp;nbsp;the team reached a peak of 5 blocking work&#xD;
    items in the iteration. The number gets smaller as the iteration nears its end, but there are still 3 remaining open&#xD;
    work items that are blocked.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&lt;img alt=&quot;Blocking Work Items Report&quot; src=&quot;resources/blocking_work_items.gif&quot; width=&quot;591&quot; height=&quot;419&quot; />&lt;br />&#xD;
&lt;h3>&#xD;
    Frequency and reporting&#xD;
&lt;/h3>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    The team reviews Blocking&amp;nbsp;Work Items throughout the iteration to understand their progress at removing road&#xD;
    blocks. This metric is also reviewed at the end of each iteration to help identify trends throughout the release.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;h3>&#xD;
    Collection and reporting tools&amp;nbsp;&#xD;
&lt;/h3>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Use IBM&amp;reg; Rational&amp;reg; Team Concert&amp;reg; to track Blocking Work Items. An out of the box&amp;nbsp;report plots all open work items&#xD;
    with&amp;nbsp;a severity of &amp;nbsp;&quot;Blocker&quot; over time.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&lt;br /></mainDescription>
